<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-674-530  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 674 530.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Banking  July 1990 v7 n7 p20(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Exploring the lights-out data center. (Manufacturers Hanover Corp.andO;automates its data center)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burda, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Manufacturers Hanover Corp (MHC) automates its data center byconsolidating its operations into a service-oriented group andeliminating unwieldy 'production-line' methods.andP;  MHC's automationprogram, started in 1987, reduces the number of messages beingprocessed by human staff from 100,000 to 7,000 per day.andP;  Paperhandling, scheduling and tape storage systems are reworked toreduce personnel, and the remaining staff is integrated into oneoperation.andP;  That operation's approach no longer follows the oldorganizational format, which was based on production line methods.andO;The new, service-oriented organization consists of a servicecenter for interaction with customers, a product center forcustomer input and output and a capacity center for dataprocessing.andP;  The data processing can now be done in remotelocations, that can be moved or closed as needed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Manufacturers Hanover Corp. (data processing).andO;Ticker:    MHC.andO;Topic:     Information CentersManagement of EDPCase StudyProductivityCost ReductionAutomation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>